Lizeka Tandwa, News24David Lipshitz (Screengrab) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Johannesburg &ndash; After losing his father in a tragic murder which should have left him shattered, David Lipshitz was instead driven to excel and be one of the best students at his school.&nbsp;-&nbsp;Get your matric results first on News24Lipshitz, from King David High School in Linksfield, bagged five distinctions in this year&rsquo;s IEB matric exams. He also suffers from Asperger's, a disorder which can significantly affect ones social interactions.&nbsp;- Health24: Asperger syndrome&ldquo;When I lost my father it was the biggest reality check I&rsquo;ve ever had. I realised the reality of life,&rdquo; he said.&nbsp;Lipshitz, known by those who love him as Dovi, said his father was his greatest role model.&nbsp; &ldquo;I wanted to be like my dad. I wanted to be a kind-hearted person. To do the best I can in every aspect of my life.&rdquo;This drive made him push himself a lot harder in his studies, he said.&nbsp;&ldquo;It just pushed me to be the best I can be. That&rsquo;s what motivated me to buckle down and to start studying hard.&rdquo;He excelled in English, History, Hebrew, History, and Life Orientation. Lipshitz said he viewed Asperger's as strength and not a weakness. The syndrome allowed him to take stock of what he had even more and to &ldquo;to value friendship and push ahead&rdquo;.&nbsp;He praised his school for affording him the space and support he needed during his school career.&nbsp;&ldquo;It is a magnificent place... The pass rate and the teaching style is phenomenal. I want to say to the next matric [students], take every moment and live it to the fullest. They must embrace what they learn there.&rdquo;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.